result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, with Attorney Sebion. This case was dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes in 15CF138.

Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.  Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the highways until properly reinstated in the State of Wisconsin.

Defendant questioned defendant on his understanding of the waiver of right to a preliminary hearing.  He stated he understood.  Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently waived his right to a preliminary hearing.
ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Sebion.  Waive reading of the complaint.
Defendant appeared by video from the Jackson County Jail.

DA Gerald Fox appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared by video from the Jackson County Jail.  Court recited the charges and possible penalties contained in the complaint.  Defendant understood.  Defendant has SPD representation on another case.  Court advised the defendant that he needs to apply for this case also.  Bond set.  AIA set for 1/25/16 at 9 am.
